sentences: Carissa Chavval Anderson (born March 2, 1986), known as iRAWniQ (pronounced "ironic"), also known as RAW, is a gender-fluid American rapper, singer, songwriter and producer.

Born in Grand Rapids, Michigan, she started as part of the electro-hiphop duo, Flying Without Wingz, in 2010, releasing five EPS while signing two distribution deals with Shake Your Ass Records as well as Dandy Kid Records.
After going solo in 2012, iRAWniQ released her mixtape as Lisa Turtle which featured Grand Hustle production credit from 2BandGeeks and a feature from newly signed Aftermath rapper, Jon Connor.

In 2014, iRAWniQ released her EP, No One Said It Would Be Easy, accompanied with three remixes and a visual directed by JB Ghuman Jr.  Her latest EP, Black Girls On Skateboards, was released in 2016, selling over 10,000 copies independently via her bandcamp.

She was adopted in 1989 by two pastors in Grand Rapids, Michigan.
Their first mixtape, The X-Files, was self-released on their Myspace page in 2009.
Their second mixtape, HipTRONica, was released in 2010 and their song "All Stars" debuted on clear channel radio in Grand Rapids, Michigan.
In 2011, they linked with producer Slade Templeton releasing their EP, Welcome To The Playground, whose single 'Playdate' scored top ten in dubstep genre on beatport.
After relocating to Los Angeles in 2012, the duo decided to go their separate ways to creatively find themselves.
She self-released her mixtape, iRAWniQ as Lisa Turtle in early 2012.
In 2014 she released her EP, "No One Said It Would Be Easy", a record about surpassing the tribulations of being an indie, gay, single-mother in the music industry.
In 2016, iRAWniQ released her EP, Black Girls On Skateboards which garnished over $10,000 in record sales on her bandcamp.
In late 2016, RAW was featured in JB Ghuman Jr's art installation, Singularity of the Soul.
This project also gave her  acclaim in the LGBTQ community, securing her an official SXSW showcase in March.
The visual took over eight months to finish from start to finish and received acclaim from Huffington Post, Vice, and LA Weekly.
